{"id":"1503.09175","submitter":"Torsten M\\\"utze","authors":"Torsten M\\\"utze, Pascal Su","title":"Bipartite Kneser graphs are Hamiltonian","comments":null,"journal-ref":"Combinatorica 37(6):1207-1219, 2017","doi":"10.1007/s00493-016-3434-6","report-no":null,"categories":"math.CO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  For integers $k\\geq 1$ and $n\\geq 2k+1$ the Kneser graph $K(n,k)$ has as\nvertices all $k$-element subsets of $[n]:=\\{1,2,\\ldots,n\\}$ and an edge between\nany two vertices (=sets) that are disjoint. The bipartite Kneser graph $H(n,k)$\nhas as vertices all $k$-element and $(n-k)$-element subsets of $[n]$ and an\nedge between any two vertices where one is a subset of the other. It has long\nbeen conjectured that all Kneser graphs and bipartite Kneser graphs except the\nPetersen graph $K(5,2)$ have a Hamilton cycle. The main contribution of this\npaper is proving this conjecture for bipartite Kneser graphs $H(n,k)$. We also\nestablish the existence of cycles that visit almost all vertices in Kneser\ngraphs $K(n,k)$ when $n=2k+o(k)$, generalizing and improving upon previous\nresults on this problem.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 31 Mar 2015 19:34:55 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 3 Jun 2015 06:40:29 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Fri, 9 Oct 2015 07:59:56 GMT"}],"update_date":"2018-02-16"}
